k is meticulously researched, and draws from archives that have never been addressed in this way before. Its highly original and innovative approach, which combines comparative analysis with a focus on transcolonial connections, puts the book at the forefront of current postcolonial scholarship. The insights that Masters and servants provides into the domestic politics of colonial rule make this book essential reading for students and scholars of empire.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHousehold employeeszAustraliazDarwin (N.T.)xHistoryy19th century. 0aHousehold employeeszGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aHousehold employeeszSingaporexHistoryy19th century. 4aStudies in Imperialism 2017. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh  aBritish empire.  aChinese.  aDarwin.  aSingapore.  adomestic service.  ahouseboys.  atranscolonial.  atropical colonialism.  awhite Australia.1 aLowrie, Claire, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2016 eBook-Packagez978311128282440uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978178499749640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781784997496423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781784997496/original  a978-3-11-128282-4  Manchester University Press 2016 eBook-Packageb2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles